The United Nations (UN) is an international organization whose stated aims are facilitating cooperation in international law, international security, economic development, social progress, human rights, and achievement of world peace. The UN was founded in 1945 after World War II to replace the League of Nations, to stop wars between countries, and to provide a platform for dialogue. It contains multiple subsidiary organizations to carry out its missions. The United Nations Charter was signed in 1945, and the UN officially came into existence on 24 October 1945, when the Charter had been ratified by China, France, the Soviet Union, the United Kingdom, the United States and by a majority of other signatories. Muscle tissue is organized into individual muscle fibers that are composed of many sarcomeres (basic functional unit of a muscle). Sarcomeres are composed of myofibrils (basic functional unit of a muscle), which are in turn composed of thick filaments and thin filaments. The thin filaments are composed of actin (a protein) and tropomyosin (a protein), while the thick filaments are composed of myosin (a protein) and tropomyosin.
